FYI/background from The Economist: “Today the Senate Judiciary Committee convenes to consider Amy Coney Barrett, President Donald Trump’s nominee to replace the late liberal justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg on America’s Supreme Court. The confirmation hearing for Ms Barrett, a conservative appeals-court judge, will be the first for a SCOTUS seat to be held partially by video-conference. At least two Republican committee members have tested positive for covid-19 and will participate virtually. Over the coming days senators will probe Ms Barrett’s views on matters including health care and abortion, and may press her to explain whether a letter she signed urging “the unborn to be protected in law” means she would jettison Roe v Wade . If, as expected, Ms Barrett gets the committee’s nod, a full Senate vote will follow in late October. Mr Trump hopes to seat his nominee before the election, but infected Republicans might complicate this plan. Senate rules require this tally to take place in person.“

- Senate has explicitly rejected fewer than 2 percent of all cabinet nominees since 1789, nearly a quarter of all Supreme Court nominations have failed to be confirmed. (Base rate 75%) - Supreme Court Justices are confirmed by the Senate via a simple majority - Republicans have a 53-47 majority (+) -Senators Susan Collins of Maine and Lisa Murkowski of Alaska, have said they oppose holding a vote to confirm a Supreme Court justice before the election (51-49) - If 3 senators (COVID) are unable to vote (must be physically present to vote ) Barrett will not be confirmed (-) - 3 senate judiciary senators are in quarantine - VP is the tiebreaker in the event of a split (for Barrett) -According to the Congressional Research Service, the average number of days from nomination to final Senate vote since 1975 is 67 days (2.2 months), while the median is 71 days (or 2.3 months) (-) - Barrett was nominated on 26 Sep, 38 days before the election (-) - Confirmation hearing planned for 12 Oct and vote on 22 Oct (+) - Senate is projected to be split or flip to Democrate (a vote after 3 nov would be highly unlikely in this case)

Outside View: Decided to look first at: what is the average number of days (and median number of days) that pass between nomination and confirmation? Per Wikipedia (which cites Congressional Research Service, which is an authoritative source): According to the Congressional Research Service, the average number of days from nomination to final Senate vote since 1975 is 67 days (2.2 months), while the median is 71 days (or 2.3 months).[19][20] https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Appointment_and_confirmation_to_the_Supreme_Court_of_the_United_States#:~:text=According%20to%20the%20Congressional%20Research,days%20(or%202.3%20months).

A re-hearing would be consistent with the Court’s practice in several close cases in 2016 after the death of Justice Scalia left the Court with eight members for about a year.

With Senator Romney and Sens. Garder and McSally (both on the ballot in 2020) signaling their support for moving forward with ACB, that appears to pave the way for her confirmation by the Senate. The larger question now is the timing of the nomination. It appears that the Republican caucus is prepared to move rapidly with her nomination. She has already visited 19 Republican Senators in her first two days of hill meetings (a tradition among nominees is to offer a meeting to every sitting Senator). Although Democrats are still deciding on their tactics for how to handle the situation, they do not hold any silver bullet to stop the train and few options to slow it down. With the books cleared of other legislative issues (other than coronavirus relief), it would appear we are on track for mid-Oct hearings. This would likely set up a floor vote in mid-to-late October. Given the possibility of election court challenges, this would seem to increase the likelihood of a quick nomination. The only possibility for a lame-duck confirmation would likely be from Senators on the ballot in 2020 with close races. Spending time in Washington and not on the campaign trail could cause some concern among those Senators but seems unlikely to slow things down enough to slip pass the elections.
